## What is MFA?
Multi-Factor Authentication requires users to prove their 
identity using at least 2 factors:
- Something you know (password)
- Something you have (phone)
- Something you are (fingerprint)

A password alone can be stolen. MFA means even if a hacker 
gets the password, they still can't sign in without the 
user's phone. Microsoft states MFA blocks 99.9% of 
account compromise attacks.

---

## Three Ways to Enable MFA

| Method | Description | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| Security Defaults | Microsoft enables MFA for everyone | Small orgs, quick setup |
| Per-user MFA | Enable per individual user | Legacy method |
| Conditional Access | Smart MFA based on risk | Enterprise best practice |

